{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1589"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1589"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.59,0.05,0.06,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1589"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35329"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"9160"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with an abdominal lump that he has had for a couple of years, accompanied by occasional mild abdominal pain. His medical history includes asthma and type 2 diabetes. The only medication he takes is metformin. He is a non-smoker and drinks two cans of beer a day. On examination, his blood pressure is 132/84 mmHg, pulse 76/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His BMI is 35 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The physical examination is unremarkable apart from a midline abdominal swelling (Image). The lump is reducible, and there is a 1 cm defect in the linea alba immediately above the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Watch and wait","Weight reducing diet","Abdominal wall binder","Abdominal wall exercises","Surgical repair"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man has a para-umbilical hernia. This should be repaired, but to achieve a good surgical result, this patient should be encouraged to \u003Cstrong\u003Elose some weight\u003C/strong\u003E before undertaking a repair. In adults, para-umbilical hernias can be precipitated by obesity, pregnancies, and other conditions which weaken the abdominal muscles and fascia. If this patient had symptoms of strangulation or obstruction of the contents within the hernia, then \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgery\u003C/strong\u003E would be first-line. However, with a 1 cm defect, this complication is unlikely, and his weight should be addressed first before conducting non-urgent surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this was a case of divarication of the recti, then weight loss and abdominal wall exercises would be sufficient advice. An abdominal wall divarication is often mistaken for a hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatch and wait\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most appropriate management from these options provided as whilst there is no immediate risk, the para-umbilical hernias are likely to increase in size over time and thus increase the risk of strangulation or obstruction. Reducing his weight would help to reduce the risk factor (obesity) and the success in surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal wall binder\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered for hernias in obese individuals who are not considered fit for surgery but is not indicated as first-line management in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal wall exercises\u003C/strong\u003E are unlikely to improve the hernia as it is not due to a weakness of the abdominal muscles but more so the abdominal wall itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn infants and children, the management of an umbilical hernia is different. Between 10-20% of children will have an umbilical hernia, and these usually close spontaneously by age 4-5 years. Surgery in the paediatric population is indicated for persistence of the umbilical hernia past 4-5 years of age, or if there are any signs of strangulation - a rare complication in a true umbilical hernia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Getting patients to lose weight usually improves their surgical prospects."],"references":["Muysoms FE, Miserez M, Berrevoet F, et al. Classification of primary and incisional abdominal wall hernias. Hernia 2009; 13:407\u201314. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19495920/","Paiva de Oliveira G, Maillo C. Prehabilitation: Enhancing reccover and outcomes in hernia surgery. Hernia update and approaches. Available at: https://www.intechopen.com/chapters/1139873"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35329"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1589"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19192"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19192"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a71ea1a-6d1e-410a-8d77-f0e319550f76.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a71ea1a-6d1e-410a-8d77-f0e319550f76.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":383,"height":506}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35329"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-06T21:26:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-0